[INAUDIBLE] 10 pounds
for a five mile trip

00:46:17.274 --> 00:46:19.263
on the [INAUDIBLE]
railway, and you

00:46:19.263 --> 00:46:21.096
get to [INAUDIBLE] and
you pay seven pounds,

00:46:21.096 --> 00:46:24.670
[INAUDIBLE] throughout
[INAUDIBLE].

00:46:24.670 --> 00:46:27.652
How much of that is steam's
really, really expensive,

00:46:27.652 --> 00:46:31.102
and how much of that is just
because [INAUDIBLE] huge costs?

00:46:31.102 --> 00:46:32.810
SIMON BRADLEY: How
inefficient was steam?

00:46:32.810 --> 00:46:35.500
It was massively, crippling,
staggeringly inefficient

00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:36.432
is the answer.

00:46:36.432 --> 00:46:38.140
When it's the only
way of doing anything,

00:46:38.140 --> 00:46:42.090
yes, it's more efficient than
a horse, and a horse and cart.

00:46:42.090 --> 00:46:45.320
But a great deal of the
coal burnt by the locomotive

00:46:45.320 --> 00:46:46.840
just flies out of the chimney.

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:48.530
It doesn't burn
it as efficiently

00:46:48.530 --> 00:46:49.930
as a power station does.

00:46:49.930 --> 00:46:52.400
So that's one reason
why electrification

00:46:52.400 --> 00:46:54.350
is more efficient
than steam, and why

00:46:54.350 --> 00:46:56.225
they tried to electrify
as soon as they could

00:46:56.225 --> 00:46:58.030
when they could afford it.

00:46:58.030 --> 00:47:01.010
Other than that, they
spent a huge amount of time

00:47:01.010 --> 00:47:04.440
just coming to the boil,
or having to be emptied

00:47:04.440 --> 00:47:05.570
and cleaned out afterwards.

00:47:05.570 --> 00:47:08.340
Because you can't just keep
them burning the whole time.

00:47:08.340 --> 00:47:13.490
You have to make up the
fire, and then take fire out.

00:47:13.490 --> 00:47:16.692
The water clogs the
boiler up with scale.

00:47:16.692 --> 00:47:18.650
They've got huge numbers
of moving parts, which

00:47:18.650 --> 00:47:21.320
require constant attention.

00:47:21.320 --> 00:47:22.610
Where do you stop, really?

00:47:22.610 --> 00:47:24.220
So and they were cheap to build.

00:47:24.220 --> 00:47:25.178
That's the other thing.

00:47:25.178 --> 00:47:27.650
They were much cheaper to build
than diesels or electrics.

00:47:27.650 --> 00:47:29.817
So one of the wrong
turnings in railway history

00:47:29.817 --> 00:47:31.900
after the Second World War
was to say, well, look.

00:47:31.900 --> 00:47:32.700
Here we are.

00:47:32.700 --> 00:47:34.932
We've got all this coal.

00:47:34.932 --> 00:47:36.390
Oil is something
we have to import,

00:47:36.390 --> 00:47:38.592
because there was no
North Sea oil then.

00:47:38.592 --> 00:47:41.020
And electrification will do
it when we can afford it.

00:47:41.020 --> 00:47:44.860
But in the meantime, we've got
lots more steam locomotives.

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:46.030
This is extraordinary.

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:48.110
The last steam locomotive
for the national system

00:47:48.110 --> 00:47:51.452
for British Railways
was built in 1960.

00:47:51.452 --> 00:47:53.160
And even then, they
thought it might have

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:55.670
a working life of 20 years.

00:47:55.670 --> 00:47:59.160
And in 1955, they were
talking about steam maybe

00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:01.939
lasting into the mid-1980s.

00:48:01.939 --> 00:48:04.480
And that sounds weird until you
look at some other countries.

00:48:04.480 --> 00:48:09.010
Because West Germany, as it
used to be before reunification,

00:48:09.010 --> 00:48:12.330
which had a much more phased
program of modernization

00:48:12.330 --> 00:48:14.690
and didn't have the mass
closures that we had,

00:48:14.690 --> 00:48:16.330
the last steamhaul
passenger trains

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:18.130
in West Germany,
modern West Germany,

00:48:18.130 --> 00:48:22.020
where all the modern stuff
comes from, ran in 1977.

00:48:22.020 --> 00:48:26.021
So railway history is full
of surprises like that.

00:48:26.021 --> 00:48:27.354
MALE SPEAKER: I've got one here.

00:48:27.354 --> 00:48:29.764
AUDIENCE: So you said in
European [INAUDIBLE] railways

00:48:29.764 --> 00:48:32.174
being continuously
rocked by innovation.

00:48:32.174 --> 00:48:35.786
As a naive observer, it
looks like nothing much has

00:48:35.786 --> 00:48:36.994
changed in the last 30 years.

00:48:36.994 --> 00:48:38.035
Is that impression right?

00:48:38.035 --> 00:48:40.152
Or has a lot of stuff changed?

00:48:40.152 --> 00:48:42.360
SIMON BRADLEY: Has innovation
stopped on the railway?

00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:44.438
Yeah, I don't think it has.

00:48:48.140 --> 00:48:51.970
At the headline end, the British
Rail did have a research centre

00:48:51.970 --> 00:48:53.665
at Darby.

00:48:53.665 --> 00:48:55.290
It still goes on
doing bits and pieces,

00:48:55.290 --> 00:48:57.456
but that was one of the
casualties of privatisation,

00:48:57.456 --> 00:48:58.460
really.

00:48:58.460 --> 00:49:01.330
And the railways had,
from innovation happening

00:49:01.330 --> 00:49:03.270
in haphazard ways, like
Edmondson inventing

00:49:03.270 --> 00:49:07.150
his tickets, the railways
to tried to harness it.

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:09.151
So there was a staff
college, and then

00:49:09.151 --> 00:49:10.150
laboratories and things.

00:49:10.150 --> 00:49:11.358
All that happens in the '30s.

00:49:11.358 --> 00:49:14.050
So it has about a
50 year lifespan

00:49:14.050 --> 00:49:18.440
of being at the core of what
the railways are trying to do.

00:49:18.440 --> 00:49:21.560
But I think it's gone
massively international,

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:23.600
and that's part of it.

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:25.950
In this country, it's
suffered from privatisation,

00:49:25.950 --> 00:49:29.440
because all the
uncertainties associated

00:49:29.440 --> 00:49:33.900
with it, rather than necessarily
the private model in itself.

00:49:33.900 --> 00:49:38.672
But track continues
to evolve and change.

00:49:38.672 --> 00:49:40.880
The ways in which things
are done are more efficient.

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:44.330
And I think what isn't seen
quite so much is safety.

00:49:44.330 --> 00:49:45.970
The critics within
the system say

00:49:45.970 --> 00:49:48.330
the railways are now
too obsessed with safety

00:49:48.330 --> 00:49:50.820
down to tiny little
imagined hazards,

00:49:50.820 --> 00:49:53.680
little fences going up
at the ends of platforms.

00:49:53.680 --> 00:49:54.530
For what?

00:49:54.530 --> 00:49:56.120
To stop stray dogs or something?

00:49:56.120 --> 00:49:56.790
Or to stop you walking off?

00:49:56.790 --> 00:49:58.664
If you want to jump onto
a train, believe me.

00:49:58.664 --> 00:49:59.880
You're going to do it.

00:49:59.880 --> 00:50:04.330
But there's a lot of
spotting the possible hazard

00:50:04.330 --> 00:50:05.430
thing going on.

00:50:05.430 --> 00:50:08.460
It's quite expensive
to make those changes,

00:50:08.460 --> 00:50:12.590
but the general
impetus is a good one.

00:50:12.590 --> 00:50:16.910
I think it's eight years now
since a passenger or a worker

00:50:16.910 --> 00:50:19.149
was killed on the railways.

00:50:19.149 --> 00:50:20.940
Eight used to be about
the number of people

00:50:20.940 --> 00:50:22.314
killed on the
railways every day.

00:50:22.314 --> 00:50:26.690
That was when there were so
many men working on the tracks

00:50:26.690 --> 00:50:30.670
coupling things up like
the people you see there.

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:32.420
Huge wagons are being
shunted up and down.

00:50:32.420 --> 00:50:35.350
You've got to go between
them to couple them together.

00:50:35.350 --> 00:50:38.320
The driver isn't paying
attention, or somebody's tired,

00:50:38.320 --> 00:50:39.080
or somebody slips.

00:50:39.080 --> 00:50:42.120
At the very least,
you might lose a limb.

00:50:42.120 --> 00:50:46.980
So the railways used to
kill people all the time,

00:50:46.980 --> 00:50:48.200
and now they don't.

00:50:48.200 --> 00:50:51.230
So I think part of it
is about risk as well.

00:50:53.874 --> 00:50:54.790
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:05.740
SIMON BRADLEY: No.

00:51:05.740 --> 00:51:07.490
I would have loved to
have seen it happen.

00:51:07.490 --> 00:51:11.040
Sleeper trains are a
special private enthusiasm.

00:51:11.040 --> 00:51:12.820
Do go on them if
you get a chance.

00:51:12.820 --> 00:51:14.110
They're still there.

00:51:14.110 --> 00:51:17.964
But what you can't do is
sleep under the tunnel.

00:51:17.964 --> 00:51:20.380
You used to be able to do it
on something called the night

00:51:20.380 --> 00:51:22.756
ferry, incidentally, that
left Victoria and was

00:51:22.756 --> 00:51:25.130
pushed onto a train ferry and
taken off at the other end.

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:26.546
You would sleep
your way to Paris,

00:51:26.546 --> 00:51:29.080
but that stopped in 1980.

00:51:29.080 --> 00:51:34.690
But no, the answer is actually
it's a fall in air prices.

00:51:34.690 --> 00:51:38.050
Air travel prices,
cheap flights,

00:51:38.050 --> 00:51:41.360
the deregulation
of air travel, that

00:51:41.360 --> 00:51:43.850
was what really wrecked
the business model.

00:51:43.850 --> 00:51:46.680
But it was too late to stop
them from building lots and lots

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:49.365
of very high spec
sleeper carriages,

00:51:49.365 --> 00:51:50.740
which were meant
to do just that.

00:51:50.740 --> 00:51:52.615
You would have been able
to get on the train.

00:51:52.615 --> 00:51:53.890
And it was very political.

00:51:53.890 --> 00:51:56.479
You had to have direct services
from Wales and Scotland

00:51:56.479 --> 00:51:57.270
as well as England.

00:51:57.270 --> 00:52:00.170
You would be able to get
on the train in Glasgow,

00:52:00.170 --> 00:52:03.592
and then you would dine as
you passed through England.

00:52:03.592 --> 00:52:05.050
And then you'd go
under the tunnel,

00:52:05.050 --> 00:52:07.770
and you'd wake up in
Berlin or something.

00:52:07.770 --> 00:52:09.880
And they built these things.

00:52:09.880 --> 00:52:12.650
But then the project was
cancelled before they'd even

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:14.900
turned a wheel in
actual service.

00:52:14.900 --> 00:52:18.680
And these great white
elephant-- you can understand

00:52:18.680 --> 00:52:20.826
there was a lot of
desire to hush this up,

00:52:20.826 --> 00:52:22.450
because it was all
rather embarrassing.

00:52:22.450 --> 00:52:26.870
And I excavated a bit of the
story in this John Prescott

00:52:26.870 --> 00:52:30.050
rant to the House of Commons
in 1999 or something,

00:52:30.050 --> 00:52:32.565
saying that I've
suddenly been asked

00:52:32.565 --> 00:52:36.261
to come up with 200 million
for these carriages.

00:52:36.261 --> 00:52:37.260
There's no use for them.

00:52:37.260 --> 00:52:39.260
They don't work, and
they're sitting in a field,

00:52:39.260 --> 00:52:40.290
or something like that.

00:52:40.290 --> 00:52:42.770
But they did manage to sell
some of them to, I think,

00:52:42.770 --> 00:52:44.270
the Canadian railways.

00:52:44.270 --> 00:52:50.350
And now you can sleep your
way through the Rockies

00:52:50.350 --> 00:52:54.410
or wherever the great Canadian
cross-continental journeys go.

00:52:54.410 --> 00:52:57.230
But yeah, it was thought to
be the future with the Channel

00:52:57.230 --> 00:53:00.807
Tunnel and the continuing
sleeper service.

00:53:00.807 --> 00:53:02.890
And the answer is that,
yes, it's air competition.

00:53:02.890 --> 00:53:05.290
Again, it's almost like
a miniature retread

00:53:05.290 --> 00:53:06.910
of what British
railways got wrong

00:53:06.910 --> 00:53:10.830
in the '50s of not plotting
the graph as to bigger lorries,

00:53:10.830 --> 00:53:12.090
better lorries, motorways.

00:53:12.090 --> 00:53:14.450
They didn't see
motorways coming.

00:53:14.450 --> 00:53:16.529
So yeah.

00:53:16.529 --> 00:53:18.577
MALE SPEAKER: Time for
one more quick question.

00:53:18.577 --> 00:53:19.910
There's a gentleman [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:24.257 --> 00:53:25.668
Right here.

00:53:25.668 --> 00:53:27.167
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm
just wondering how

00:53:27.167 --> 00:53:29.846
you feel the British
rail service compares

00:53:29.846 --> 00:53:32.768
against the international
competitors.

00:53:32.768 --> 00:53:37.638
Do you think the British people
are too harsh on rail service?

00:53:37.638 --> 00:53:39.586
[INAUDIBLE] international
service to the EU

00:53:39.586 --> 00:53:42.434
would be admired
significantly more

00:53:42.434 --> 00:53:43.600
than what we have in the UK?

00:53:46.908 --> 00:53:49.720
SIMON BRADLEY: Yes,
foreign comparisons.

00:53:49.720 --> 00:53:51.484
I'm not the best
person to answer that,

00:53:51.484 --> 00:53:53.650
partly because while I've
been working on this book,

00:53:53.650 --> 00:53:55.910
I've been traveling
on the British railway

00:53:55.910 --> 00:53:59.620
system for research
purposes in my spare time

00:53:59.620 --> 00:54:01.730
rather than traveling
abroad so much.

00:54:01.730 --> 00:54:03.790
But I think one
thing that is missed

00:54:03.790 --> 00:54:07.480
is the density
density of traffic.

00:54:07.480 --> 00:54:13.690
It's the number of fast
and efficient trains

00:54:13.690 --> 00:54:15.352
that are running all the time.

00:54:15.352 --> 00:54:17.560
It's the sheer numbers on
the move, the numbers going

00:54:17.560 --> 00:54:19.851
in and out of Berlin, numbers
going in and out of Paris

00:54:19.851 --> 00:54:23.710
by train, the numbers shuttling
back and forth between cities

00:54:23.710 --> 00:54:24.210
abroad.

00:54:24.210 --> 00:54:26.360
It just doesn't compare.

00:54:26.360 --> 00:54:28.712
And it's always been like that.

00:54:28.712 --> 00:54:32.490
The British steamhauled
railways had the highest number

00:54:32.490 --> 00:54:35.640
of the fastest
trains in the world.

00:54:35.640 --> 00:54:40.950
The special high speed
lines, that's shifting it.

00:54:40.950 --> 00:54:43.300
But what we've only
got one of those,

00:54:43.300 --> 00:54:47.640
and it only goes from London
to the Channel Tunnel.

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:50.150
So it's what's been achieved
on what's essentially a 19th

00:54:50.150 --> 00:54:53.260
century route map, and
very often 19th century

00:54:53.260 --> 00:54:56.790
infrastructure--- bridges,
viaducts, and things--

00:54:56.790 --> 00:54:58.120
within the limits.

00:54:58.120 --> 00:55:00.570
Because when they built the
Liverpool and Manchester

00:55:00.570 --> 00:55:03.400
in 1830, the idea
that trains would ever

00:55:03.400 --> 00:55:05.560
be electrified and travel
at 100 miles an hour,

00:55:05.560 --> 00:55:09.930
and weigh 8 to 10 times as much,
and the whole thing not fall

00:55:09.930 --> 00:55:12.530
apart, that would
have been mysterious.

00:55:12.530 --> 00:55:17.374
If they'd had better ability
to calculate their risk factors

00:55:17.374 --> 00:55:18.790
and loadings and
things, then they

00:55:18.790 --> 00:55:20.980
wouldn't have built them
as sturdily as they did.

00:55:20.980 --> 00:55:23.390
But they tended to err
on the side of caution.

00:55:23.390 --> 00:55:27.130
So a Victorian railway viaduct,
Brunel's extraordinarily

00:55:27.130 --> 00:55:31.780
elegant spare and an
amazingly flat bridge

00:55:31.780 --> 00:55:35.120
across the Thames at Maidenhead
has carried the high speed

00:55:35.120 --> 00:55:36.430
trains for years and years.

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:38.846
And now it's going to carry
the electric trains going even

00:55:38.846 --> 00:55:41.400
faster, and it's still there.

00:55:41.400 --> 00:55:42.950
Who'd have guessed it?

00:55:42.950 --> 00:55:48.000
So I wouldn't say it's
doing the best of a bad job,

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:53.850
but really pushing the what
we've got to its limits.

00:55:53.850 --> 00:55:58.900
Actually that should be a cause
for modest national pride,

00:55:58.900 --> 00:55:59.617
perhaps.

00:55:59.617 --> 00:56:01.450
MALE SPEAKER: Please
join me, and thank you.

00:56:01.450 --> 00:56:03.000
Thank you so much.

